  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Edict Appointing Ministers Yi Yeon-su and Choe U
  author: Yi Baek-sun
  language: eng
  text: 'Thus it is said: When virtue is noble, honor in ceremony flows abundantly. When merit stands high, rank becomes weighty. Such is the eternal principle of all ages. You, minister—you have counseled the royal way and decided the nation''s affairs. Outwardly you have repelled the barbarian lands; inwardly you have pacified the people. In this manner you have preserved the realm as flawless as a golden vessel. Your virtue is thus profound, your accomplishments vast. If we do not bestow upon you the reward you merit, how can justice prevail? Does not the tradition say, ''When the court appoints a man to office, it shares this decision with worthy gentlemen''? Now we grant you this appointment.'
  footnotes:
    - The 'golden vessel' (金甌) is a metaphor for an intact, perfect realm—a common phrase in East Asian political discourse symbolizing territorial and administrative wholeness.
    - The quoted reference alludes to ancient precedent whereby worthy officials were appointed through consultation and consensus among the educated class.
